node.text:
It’s the first day of school for us today, and I thought I’d share some of my back to school traditions with you. I share them every year, so if you’ve been around a while, you’ve heard these before. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We make pancakes in the shape of my son’s grade for the first day of school each year. We started with a K in kindergarten and this year we’ll be making “fifth grade pancakes.” Pancakes are his favorite breakfast, so this makes it extra special. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
My husband and I both go with him to class and walk him to his room on the first day. We couldn’t do it last year due to COVID, and I’m so glad we can this year. Since he’s a 5th grader, this will be the last year ever that I’ll get to walk him to his class on the first day of school. 😭😭😭#theygrowupsofast 
⁣⁣
Then I always take the day off, so I can be there at the bus stop to pick him up when he gets home from school. Since COVID, I’ve been mainly working from home, so no need to burn a vacation day and I can still be at the bus stop when he gets home. Yayyy!
⁣
Finally, I bake him freshly made chocolate chip cookies and serve them with milk for an after school snack. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We have done this every year (K, 1, 2, 3 and 4) and this will be our 6th year with these little traditions. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I love these traditions because they are simple and frugal, and my son looks forward to them each year. ⁣⁣You don’t have to spend a fortune to create lasting memories. Truth be told some of my most favorite childhood memories are the simple ones. 
⁣⁣
So what about you? When do your kids start school? Do you have any traditions for the start of a new school year? I’d love for you to share them below!

node.text:
I haven’t updated this chart since May, so it’s time. This shows everything I’ve invested each month during 2021 and includes 401(k), IRA, and HSA contributions. The 401(k) number in July also includes a $500 employer bonus contribution, for a grand total of $21,942 invested so far this year, as of the end of July. 

We’ve also done a number of home improvements and started a new-to-me car fund that we’ve heavily funded, so while this investment number feels like it should be higher, I’m pleased with our progress so far. 

My financial goals for this year have changed so much, and if I’m being honest, I need to sit down and map out what I want to accomplish by the end of the year. Truth is, at this exact moment, I don’t exactly know. Time to figure it out! 

Do you know what you want to accomplish, financially, by year-end? We’ve got a little over 4 months left to get it done!

node.text:
Hello friends! It’s been a while! I’ve taken an unexpected break from posting, and I’ve gotta admit, life untethered to a phone is quite beautiful. 

I’m not sure what the future holds for this account. Whether I’ll return to posting daily, or as the moment strikes, or not at all. 

As I suspected, after I left the practice of law back in March, my interest in this account started to dwindle. I wasn’t miserable in my life anymore, and without that misery, I wasn’t desperately motivated to obsess over my finances. I didn’t need financial independence to escape the hell-on-earth life I’d created for myself. I’m finally happy—working a job I actually enjoy and that pays beautifully. 

So, I just don’t know. But I had a moment today and came across a quote in one of my notebooks I thought I’d share with anyone who’s climbing that mountain, trying to dig themselves out of debt or accomplish any task that, at times, feels impossible: 

It’s from Ruth Soukup’s book Do It Scared, and it goes like this: 

“Trust the process and understand that it’s supposed to be hard. If it were easy, everyone would be doing it. Remember, the greatest accomplishments are the ones you have to work for.”

You’ve got this. 💗

node.text:
I get asked all the time how to begin this debt free journey. This is as simple as it gets right here.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I also have lots of tips for paying down debt and getting started on my saved stories under Resources. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
And, a free guide that explains all the different things my husband and I did to pay off six figures worth of debt. You can check that out by clicking the link in my profile and heading to Free Guide: Pay Off Your Debt Faster Than You Thought Possible. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Oh, and my favorite debt payoff strategy is the debt snowball. Find out all about how to pay off debt with that strategy (or with the debt avalanche) by hitting up the blog. ⁣⁣

⁣The biggest mistake I see people make with debt payoff is believing they won’t be able to do it and not getting started sooner as a result. ⁣
⁣
If you haven’t begun aggressively paying off your debt, what’s stopping you? Don’t let the false belief that you can’t do it be the reason. Trust me, you CAN. ⁣

Today’s tip? Download (and use!) a personal finance app.

What are some of your faves?

node.text:
Blah. The year isn’t even half over yet and I’ve already spent more on gasoline this year than I did in ALL of 2020. 

I think this is true for two reasons: gas prices are much higher this year, and at the end of March, I started working in the office twice a week. 

I’m not kidding when I say I saved literally thousands between gasoline and tolls by working from home all last year. 

My new company is making noises that we’ll all be expected to go back to the office full time in September. 😭😭😭 I am not ready for it! Nor am I ready for all the associated increased expenses with having to commute to the office daily. So gross. 

What’s your work situation look like? If you’re working, are you working from home? Back in the office? 

App is Charlie Finance, btw, and I love it!

node.text:
I’ve been falling off the posting wagon lately. I always check in on my goals mid-month, and I totally forgot to this month. So here’s your monthly reminder to check in on those goals and re-adjust the plan as necessary. 

Here’s what I wanted to accomplish in June: 

1️⃣✅ Increase 401(k) contributions by 1%. Goal met! I’ve been doing this monthly for the last 3 months, and I think I’ve finally found my sweet spot.

2️⃣✅ Start a Back-to-School sinking fund. Goal complete! I added $150 to this fund in June and will add to it throughout the summer. It’ll cover school supplies and new clothes/shoes for the upcoming school year for my 5th grader. 

3️⃣✅ Invest $3,000. Goal met! I got paid yesterday, and immediately sent $707.69 to my HSA, which was enough to bring my total June investing to $3,000 even. 🙌🏻 

How’s your June going? What did you want to accomplish this month? Still plenty of time!!

node.text:
I know it’s not Wednesday and time got away from me yesterday, but I still wanted to give you one simple task you can do this week to improve your financial health! 

I did this last year and lowered by bill by a LOT—by simply asking. 

I just called my cell phone provider and said “I’ve been a customer for 12 years. What can we do today to make sure it’ll be 13?” 😜 

And they gave me a significant discount on my bill! 

Remember the answer is always no unless you ask! 

Have you ever tried something like this?!
#onethingwednesday
